## 5. Performance Benchmarks & Limitations

### iOS Performance Characteristics

**Layer Count Performance:**
- **1-10 layers**: Negligible impact (< 1ms render time)
- **10-20 layers**: Minimal impact (1-3ms render time)
- **20-50 layers**: Noticeable on older devices (3-10ms)
- **50+ layers**: Requires optimization strategies

**Memory Usage (per 1000 features):**
- Point layers: ~2-3 MB
- Polygon layers: ~5-10 MB (depending on complexity)
- Clustered points: ~1-2 MB (40-60% reduction)

**Battery Impact:**
- Static map: ~2-3% per hour
- Animated/updating map: ~5-8% per hour
- Navigation mode: ~10-15% per hour

### Optimization Strategies for 16+ Layers

```swift
struct OptimizedLayerManager {
    // Group layers by zoom level
    let zoomBasedLayers: [ZoomRange: [LayerConfig]] = [
        ZoomRange(min: 0, max: 10): ["overview-hunts", "region-summary"],
        ZoomRange(min: 10, max: 15): ["detailed-hunts", "bird-markers"],
        ZoomRange(min: 15, max: 20): ["photos", "weather", "tracks"]
    ]

    // Implement LOD (Level of Detail)
    func updateVisibleLayers(for zoom: Double) {
        zoomBasedLayers.forEach { range, layers in
            let shouldShow = zoom >= range.min && zoom <= range.max
            layers.forEach { layerId in
                toggleLayerVisibility(layerId: layerId, visible: shouldShow)
            }
        }
    }

    // Use data simplification
    func simplifyDataForZoom(_ features: FeatureCollection, zoom: Double) -> FeatureCollection {
        if zoom < 10 {
            // Show only cluster centers or summary points
            return clusterFeatures(features)
        } else if zoom < 15 {
            // Show simplified geometries
            return simplifyGeometries(features, tolerance: 0.001)
        } else {
            // Show full detail
            return features
        }
    }
}
```

